WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.360
Hi, I'm Carson. I'm an engineer on the Shiny team here at Posit. And today I'd like to

00:00:09.360 --> 00:00:16.120
show you a real basic Shiny template and show you how to get your own data into that template

00:00:16.120 --> 00:00:18.559
and start visualizing your data.

00:00:18.559 --> 00:00:24.600
Right, so on the Shiny for Python website, I'm here on the templates page, which you

00:00:24.600 --> 00:00:29.799
can find under the components menu. We think of templates as kind of just a useful combination

00:00:29.799 --> 00:00:36.400
of components, layouts, and reactivity concepts. So I'm going to start off with one of our

00:00:36.400 --> 00:00:43.160
basic apps here. On the page for this template, I get some code that I can run in my terminal

00:00:43.160 --> 00:00:51.880
to get the code for this application. Right, so I'm going to grab this Shiny create code

00:00:51.880 --> 00:00:57.480
and paste this into my terminal. And it's going to ask me for a destination directory

00:00:57.480 --> 00:01:05.040
for these files. I'm going to say basic. And then give me some instructions to open

00:01:05.040 --> 00:01:12.720
up the app file as well as install instructions, go into this directory, and then install the

00:01:12.720 --> 00:01:17.760
requirements. And then when you open up the app file in VS Code, as long as you have the

00:01:17.760 --> 00:01:22.760
Shiny VS Code extension installed, you should see a play button here up in the right hand

00:01:22.760 --> 00:01:30.239
side corner to run your Shiny app, get a live reload of my Shiny application. But really

00:01:30.239 --> 00:01:36.199
what I want to focus on here with this application is, you know, at a very high level, we just

00:01:36.199 --> 00:01:42.400
have a page title here, we have some code to render a histogram, and that histogram

00:01:42.400 --> 00:01:49.320
is reactively reading the variable from the data set that we want to be visualizing. So

00:01:49.320 --> 00:01:57.800
here this input dot bear is referencing this input select down here. And this input select

00:01:57.800 --> 00:02:08.199
has the VAR ID, the label for the input control, as well as the choices for that input select.

00:02:08.199 --> 00:02:16.000
So these choices here are specific to the data set that this is visualizing. So these,

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:22.199
the names here are very intentional and are referring to the columns in this DF data frame

00:02:22.199 --> 00:02:27.080
here. Before we actually go in and look at the details of how we're getting that DF,

00:02:27.080 --> 00:02:38.520
let's just also get a nice interactive display of this DF data frame. So here I can see the

00:02:38.520 --> 00:02:43.839
actual data frame behind this histogram below. And now if I wanted to, you know, I could

00:02:43.839 --> 00:02:48.919
add more input controls or modify this input select to look at the different variables

00:02:48.919 --> 00:02:53.800
in this data set. But let's actually have a look into how we're importing the data.

00:02:53.800 --> 00:03:00.100
So we've set up a lot of these templates to be based on this kind of approach to importing

00:03:00.100 --> 00:03:10.399
data where there is a local shared Python file. So when we say from shared import DF,

00:03:10.399 --> 00:03:18.320
that's going to execute this shared.py file. And most of these, at least at the moment,

00:03:18.320 --> 00:03:26.899
are set up to use Pandas read CSV to read in a CSV file that you also get with the template.

00:03:26.899 --> 00:03:32.880
So this is nice and easy and, you know, low dependency way to read in some data for our

00:03:32.880 --> 00:03:39.080
application. If you have larger data, you probably want to use like a more optimized

00:03:39.080 --> 00:03:44.479
file format and a more optimized way of importing that file format. So you might want to consider

00:03:44.479 --> 00:03:49.479
using something like Arrow to read in Parquet files or something like that if performance

00:03:49.479 --> 00:03:54.639
is an issue for your app when it comes to importing the data. But this also demonstrates

00:03:54.639 --> 00:04:00.600
like a useful concept when importing your data. You don't necessarily want to rely on

00:04:00.600 --> 00:04:06.259
relative file paths. Really what you want to lean into is using some sort of file structure

00:04:06.259 --> 00:04:13.539
like this, where if I can assume that the CSV file is a sibling to this shared Python

00:04:13.539 --> 00:04:21.299
file, then what I can do is leverage the double under file object to get the file location

00:04:21.299 --> 00:04:26.619
for this Python file and then get the parent directory to make sure that I'm actually in

00:04:26.619 --> 00:04:33.500
this directory for this application and then read the CSV file of the penguins.csv. So

00:04:33.500 --> 00:04:37.959
if I'm reading a file from disk, this is like a nice setup to do this in such a way

00:04:37.959 --> 00:04:43.500
that your code is very portable from machine to machine. Another advantage of setting it

00:04:43.500 --> 00:04:50.859
up in this way where you import from a local module is especially for Shiny Express. This

00:04:50.859 --> 00:04:55.820
will ensure that you're only importing the data once. There are situations where, you

00:04:55.820 --> 00:05:01.019
know, if you're not importing your data in a certain way, that data can end up getting

00:05:01.019 --> 00:05:06.260
imported twice. So again, for performance, it's kind of a nice abstraction here to put

00:05:06.260 --> 00:05:11.059
this in a separate module to do your data importing in this separate module. But just

00:05:11.059 --> 00:05:15.540
to demonstrate how we could get in a different data set here, I'm going to cheat a little

00:05:15.540 --> 00:05:22.940
bit in the sense that I'm not actually going to use a different file per se, but I'm going

00:05:22.940 --> 00:05:31.000
to leverage the fact that Seaborn prepackages data sets. We were just working with penguins,

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:38.519
but let's do tips instead. And now I'm going to call that df since my app is importing

00:05:38.519 --> 00:05:46.279
from this file and looking for an object named df. And now I'm getting some errors that are

00:05:46.279 --> 00:05:51.760
pretty expected in the sense that the Seaborn Hisplot logic is now receiving a different

00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:57.920
data set. It doesn't know what to do with this build length mm because that's not actually

00:05:58.040 --> 00:06:03.200
in the tips data set. But our render data frame is just displaying the data set that

00:06:03.200 --> 00:06:08.640
this new data set that we're importing from the shirt module. So I can just come to here

00:06:08.640 --> 00:06:14.600
for a nice preview of the data set that I'm working with. I can see a couple of numeric

00:06:14.600 --> 00:06:22.679
variables here, total, bill, and tip. So let's, instead of these two variables, do total bill

00:06:22.679 --> 00:06:35.799
tip. And now I have my data frame, uh, by default showing me, I believe the total tip.

00:06:35.799 --> 00:06:46.040
So let me put this data frame below the select input so that I can see the variable that

00:06:46.040 --> 00:06:51.519
I'm working with and just make sure that I can change this to tip and yep, my histogram

00:06:51.519 --> 00:06:57.799
updates to show me the new tip variable. So that in a nutshell is how we can take a

00:06:57.799 --> 00:07:03.279
template, uh, bring it down locally, get it running in VS code and bring in our own data

00:07:03.279 --> 00:07:03.640
set.

